            <span class="step-num">2</span>
            <strong>UAE Embassy</strong>
            <span>Via IVF Global</span>
          </div>
          <div class="step-arrow"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i></div>
          <div class="step-box">
            <span class="step-num">3</span>
            <strong>MOFA</strong>
            <span>In UAE</span>
          </div>
          <div class="step-arrow"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i></div>
          <div class="step-box done">
            <span class="step-num">4</span>
            <strong>Translation</strong>
            <span>MOJ Certified</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>Skip any step, and your document gets rejected. Follow all four, and it's accepted everywhere in the UAE—courts, immigration, government ministries, banks, schools, you name it.</p>

        <p>Let's break down each step.</p>

        <h2>Step 1: Getting a US Apostille</h2>

        <p>An apostille is an international certificate that verifies a document is genuine. It's attached to your original document and confirms that the signature, seal, or stamp on it is authentic.</p>

        <p>The United States is part of the Hague Apostille Convention, which standardizes this process across 124 member countries. Here's the catch: <strong>the UAE is not a member</strong>. That means a US apostille alone isn't enough—you still need UAE Embassy attestation afterward.</p>

        <p>But the apostille is still required as the first step. Without it, the UAE Embassy won't touch your document.</p>

        <h3>Where to Get Your Apostille</h3>

        <p>Apostilles come from the <strong>Secretary of State</strong> office in the state where your document was issued:</p>

        <ul class="detail-list">
          <li><strong>Birth certificate:</strong> State where you were born</li>
          <li><strong>Marriage certificate:</strong> State where you got married</li>
          <li><strong>Divorce decree:</strong> State where the divorce was finalized</li>
          <li><strong>University degree:</strong> State where the school is located</li>
          <li><strong>FBI background check:</strong> US Department of State (federal level—different process)</li>
        </ul>

