        <h2>Step 4: Arabic Translation (MOJ-Certified)</h2>

        <p>The attestation chain makes your document legally valid in the UAE. But if it's in English (which all US documents are), it still needs to be translated into Arabic before any official body will process it.</p>

        <p>Not just any translation—it must be done by a translator registered with the UAE <strong>Ministry of Justice (MOJ)</strong>.</p>

        <h3>Why MOJ Certification Matters</h3>

        <p>The UAE doesn't accept generic translations, even from professional translators. MOJ-certified translations include:</p>

